SIMPLE: prodigious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prodigious
<hw>Pro*di"gious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>prodigiosus</ets>, fr. <ets>prodigium</ets> a prodigy; cf. F.
<ets>prodigieux</ets>. See <er>Prodigy</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Of the nature of a prodigy; marvelous; wonderful;
portentous.</def> <mark>[Obs. or R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is <qex>prodigious</qex> to have thunder in a clear sky.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir T. Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Extraordinary in bulk, extent, quantity, or degree;
very great; vast; huge; immense; <as>as, a <ex>prodigious</ex> mountain;
a <ex>prodigious</ex> creature; a <ex>prodigious</ex>
blunder.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Prodigious</xex> might.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Huge; enormous; monstrous; portentous; marvelous;
amazing; astonishing; extraordinary.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prodigiously</ent>⟦br⟧
